{
  "In the Bohr model of hydrogen, electrons orbit the nucleus in:": "",
  "Random paths through the atom": "",
  "A continuous spiral toward the nucleus": "",
  "Specific quantized orbits with defined energy levels": "",
  "Any orbit they choose": "",
  "In Bohr's model, electrons can only occupy specific orbits (energy levels) where their angular momentum is quantized: L = n*h-bar. Electrons do not radiate energy while in these stable orbits.": "",
  "The energy levels of hydrogen are given by:": "",
  "E_n = -13.6/n eV": "",
  "E_n = 13.6*n^2 eV": "",
  "E_n = -13.6/n^2 eV": "",
  "E_n = -13.6*n eV": "",
  "The energy levels of hydrogen are E_n = -13.6/n^2 eV, where n = 1, 2, 3,... The ground state (n=1) has E = -13.6 eV, and the energy approaches 0 as n approaches infinity (ionization).": "",
  "When an electron transitions from a higher to a lower energy level, the atom:": "",
  "Emits an electron": "",
  "Emits a photon": "",
  "Absorbs a neutron": "",
  "Absorbs a photon": "",
  "When an electron drops to a lower energy level, the energy difference is emitted as a photon: E_photon = hf = E_higher - E_lower.": "",
  "The ground state of hydrogen corresponds to:": "",
  "n = 0": "",
  "n = 1": "",
  "n = infinity": "",
  "n = -1": "",
  "The ground state (lowest energy) of hydrogen is n = 1, with energy E_1 = -13.6 eV. This is the most stable state of the atom.": "",
  "The ionization energy of hydrogen from the ground state is:": "",
  "13.6 eV": "",
  "27.2 eV": "",
  "3.4 eV": "",
  "10.2 eV": "",
  "Ionization energy is the energy needed to remove the electron completely (to n = infinity, E = 0). From the ground state: E_ionization = 0 - (-13.6) = 13.6 eV.": "",
  "The Balmer series of hydrogen produces visible light from transitions ending at:": "",
  "n = 4": "",
  "n = 3": "",
  "n = 2": "",
  "The Balmer series consists of transitions from higher levels (n = 3, 4, 5, ...) down to n = 2. These transitions produce photons in the visible spectrum (red through violet).": "",
