  "The quantum mechanical model of the atom describes electrons as:": "",
  "Stationary particles embedded in the nucleus": "",
  "Waves circling the nucleus": "",
  "Particles in fixed circular orbits": "",
  "Probability clouds (orbitals) described by wave functions": "",
  "The quantum mechanical model replaces Bohr's orbits with orbitals - 3D probability distributions described by the wave function. The electron is not at a definite point but has a probability of being found at various locations.": "",
  "What is the Bohr model of the atom?": "",
  "A model where electrons orbit the nucleus in quantized energy levels, with angular momentum restricted to integer multiples of h-bar": "",
  "A model where electrons are waves around the nucleus": "",
  "A model where the nucleus orbits the electrons": "",
  "A model where electrons are embedded in a positive matrix": "",
  "The Bohr model (1913) postulates that electrons orbit the nucleus in discrete energy levels. Transitions between levels produce or absorb photons. While superseded by quantum mechanics, it correctly predicts hydrogen's spectrum.": "",
  "What is an energy level in an atom?": "",
  "A continuous range of energies under most circumstances involving energy": "",
  "A specific, quantized energy that an electron in an atom can have, corresponding to a particular quantum state": "",
  "The kinetic energy of the atom as a whole without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "The total energy of the nucleus under most circumstances involving energy": "",
  "An energy level is one of the discrete, quantized energy values that an electron in an atom can possess. The electron can only exist at these specific energies, not in between.": "",
  "What is an emission spectrum?": "",
  "X-rays emitted by metals, particularly when emission considerations are weighed against competing pressures": "",
  "A continuous band of all colors when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "The spectrum of absorbed wavelengths, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "A set of discrete bright spectral lines produced when excited atoms emit photons as electrons transition to lower energy levels": "",
  "An emission spectrum is the characteristic pattern of spectral lines emitted by excited atoms. Each line corresponds to a specific electronic transition, and the pattern is unique to each element.": "",
  "What is the principal quantum number?": "",
  "The number of electrons in an atom when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "The number of protons in an atom given that prevailing number conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "The atomic mass number, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing number dynamics": "",
  "The integer n (1, 2, 3, ...) that specifies the main energy level of an electron in an atom, with higher n corresponding to higher energy": "",
  "The principal quantum number n = 1, 2, 3, ... determines the main energy level and approximate size of the electron orbital. For hydrogen, E_n = -13.6/n^2 eV.": "",
  "What is the Lyman series?": "",
  "Transitions ending at n = 3, producing infrared light, as conventional ground theory would suggest": "",
  "Transitions ending at n = 2, producing visible light according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "The series of spectral lines in hydrogen produced by transitions from higher levels to the ground state (n = 1), all in the ultraviolet region": "",
  "X-ray emission lines because conventional analysis of ground suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "The Lyman series consists of transitions from n = 2, 3, 4, ... to n = 1 (ground state). These produce UV photons because the energy differences to the ground state are large.": "",
  "What is an excited state?": "",
  "Any energy state of an atom higher than the ground state, where an electron has absorbed energy and moved to a higher energy level": "",
  "An ionized atom, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these state dynamics operate": "",
  "The lowest energy state of an atom within the broader context of state analysis": "",
  "An atom moving at high speed, since standard models of state behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "An excited state is any quantum state with higher energy than the ground state. Atoms reach excited states by absorbing photons or through collisions. They typically return to the ground state quickly by emitting photons.": "",
  "What is the Rydberg formula?": "",
  "A formula for calculating atomic mass": "",
  "A formula for nuclear binding energy": "",
  "An empirical formula that predicts the wavelengths of hydrogen spectral lines: 1/lambda = R(1/n1^2 - 1/n2^2)": "",
  "A formula for electron orbital radius": "",
  "The Rydberg formula: 1/lambda = R_H(1/n_f^2 - 1/n_i^2), where R_H = 1.097*10^7 m^-1 is the Rydberg constant. It accurately predicts all hydrogen spectral line wavelengths.": "",
  "What are quantum numbers?": "",
  "Random numbers assigned to atoms, which is consistent with how numbers mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "The number of protons and neutrons, since standard models of numbers behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "A set of integers (n, l, ml, ms) that completely describe the quantum state of an electron in an atom, specifying its energy, orbital shape, orientation, and spin": "",
  "The atomic number and mass number, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing numbers dynamics": "",
  "Four quantum numbers define each electron's state: n (principal - energy level), l (angular momentum - orbital shape), ml (magnetic - orbital orientation), and ms (spin - +1/2 or -1/2).": "",
  "What is spectroscopy?": "",
  "The study of crystal structures given that prevailing spectroscopy conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "The study of atomic nuclei given that prevailing spectroscopy conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "The study and analysis of spectra produced by the interaction of matter with electromagnetic radiation, used to identify elements and study atomic structure": "",
  "The study of electron orbits, since the relevant spectroscopy factors typically produce this outcome in practice": "",
  "Spectroscopy analyzes the electromagnetic spectrum emitted or absorbed by matter. It is used to identify elements (each has a unique spectral fingerprint), study atomic structure, and determine compositions of distant objects.": "",
  "What is the Pauli exclusion principle?": "",
  "Electrons always repel each other": "",
  "Only two electrons can exist in any atom": "",
  "Electrons must always spin in the same direction": "",
  "No two electrons in an atom can have the same set of four quantum numbers": "",
  "The Pauli exclusion principle states that no two fermions (including electrons) in an atom can occupy the same quantum state simultaneously. This limits each orbital to two electrons with opposite spins.": "",
  "A hydrogen atom transitions from n = 3 to n = 1. What is the energy of the emitted photon?": "",
  "12.09 eV": "",
  "1.89 eV": "",
  "E_3 = -13.6/9 = -1.51 eV. E_1 = -13.6 eV. E_photon = E_3 - E_1 = -1.51 - (-13.6) = 12.09 eV.": "",
  "What is the wavelength of the photon emitted during the n = 3 to n = 2 transition in hydrogen (the first Balmer line)?": "",
  "656 nm": "",
  "410 nm": "",
  "434 nm": "",
  "486 nm": "",
  "E_photon = -13.6(1/4 - 1/9) = -13.6(5/36) = 1.89 eV = 3.02e-19 J. lambda = hc/E = (6.63e-34*3e8)/3.02e-19 = 6.58e-7 m = 656 nm (red).": "",
