  "An astronomer observes a nebula emitting light at exactly 486.1 nm (the H-beta line of hydrogen). What transition produces this line?": "",
  "n = 5 to n = 2": "",
  "n = 2 to n = 1": "",
  "n = 3 to n = 2": "",
  "n = 4 to n = 2": "",
  "The H-beta line (486.1 nm) is part of the Balmer series (transitions to n = 2). E = hc/lambda = 2.55 eV. E_4 - E_2 = (-13.6/16) - (-13.6/4) = -0.85 + 3.4 = 2.55 eV. So it's n = 4 to n = 2.": "",
  "A gas discharge tube contains hydrogen. If electrons excite hydrogen atoms to the n = 5 level, how many distinct spectral lines can be emitted as the atoms return to the ground state?": "",
  "20": "",
  "10": "",
  "5": "",
  "The number of possible spectral lines from level n is n(n-1)/2 = 5*4/2 = 10. These correspond to all possible transitions: 5-4, 5-3, 5-2, 5-1, 4-3, 4-2, 4-1, 3-2, 3-1, 2-1.": "",
  "A researcher uses laser light to excite hydrogen from n = 1 to n = 4. What photon energy is required?": "",
  "12.75 eV": "",
  "E_photon = E_4 - E_1 = (-13.6/16) - (-13.6) = -0.85 + 13.6 = 12.75 eV.": "",
